Summary

Context directive plumbing day.

The work today was fundamentally about turning a new user-facing command path into a structured backend contract, then proving the runtime handled that contract without losing provenance. The day moved from shell capture to envelope handling to resolver scaffolding, and then into proof updates that classified how runtime commits should be attributed.

What I completed

Context directive shell and payload path

Added the Obsidian context command shell and payload shape in the frontend, so the composer can express context directives instead of treating them as ad hoc chat text.
Extended the slash-command contract and draft-sync coverage so the UI state stays aligned with the command envelope.
Kept the change local to the composer/chat path rather than widening into unrelated navigation or retrieval surfaces.
Context directive envelope acceptance

Added backend support for accepting the context directive envelope in the Guardian chat route.
Wired the frontend chat client to send the directive payload through the existing chat flow.
Added route coverage so the envelope is treated as a first-class input shape, not a loose special case.
Context directive resolver scaffold

Introduced a resolver scaffold for context directives in Guardian.
Added tests around the resolver behavior and chat-route directive handling, establishing a place for directive interpretation to live explicitly.
This is still scaffold-level work, but it tightens the boundary around where directive resolution belongs.
Runtime provenance proof hardening

Updated the runtime provenance proof work so commit provenance is classified more carefully.
Expanded the image-turn containment proof and its tests to reflect the revised truth about how runtime commits should be labeled and validated.
This made the proof artifacts less ambiguous about what was actually being exercised.
Important outcome

The system is no longer just accepting a new context-command idea in the UI. It now has a real envelope path, a backend route that understands it, and a resolver seam where the semantics can be enforced instead of implied.

That matters because provenance and directive handling are now being pushed into explicit contracts. The system stopped relying on informal handling of context intent and started recording a shape that can be tested, reasoned about, and hardened further.

