Narrative Log
Dev Log - 2026-05-07

Today was a contract day more than a feature day. The work kept converging on one idea: if the system is going to accept new forms of user intent, it needs to do so through explicit shapes, explicit routes, and explicit proof. Otherwise the behavior looks real from the outside while still being soft underneath.

The first part of the day pushed that idea into the chat surface. The Obsidian context command moved from shell-level affordance into a payload the composer can actually emit. That mattered because it turned context into structured data rather than a buried convention. The draft-sync test updates followed the same line: they kept the frontend honest about what state it thinks it is carrying. Nothing about that work was flashy, but it removed a lot of ambiguity from the user intent path.

From there the backend caught up. The Guardian chat route was taught to accept the context directive envelope, which is the kind of change that usually looks small until you realize it defines where meaning lives. Instead of treating directive input like incidental chat noise, the system now has a real input contract for it. The resolver scaffold goes one step further: it creates a place where directive meaning can be resolved deliberately instead of being scattered across handlers. That is still scaffold-level work, but it is the right kind of scaffold. It marks the boundary.

The proof work was the other half of the day, and it belongs in the same story. Runtime provenance is only useful if the system can say what actually happened without hand-waving, so the image-turn containment proof was tightened and the commit provenance was classified more carefully. That kind of work rarely reads as product progress, but it is the difference between a system that merely runs and a system whose behavior can be trusted after the fact. The proof artifacts became more specific about what they were showing and what they were not.

The deeper shift is that the system is starting to separate intention, envelope, and provenance. Those are different layers, and when they blur together, the whole thing gets hard to reason about. Today’s changes made the layers more legible. The user-facing command path became more structured, the backend accepted it as a real contract, and the proof layer stopped pretending that vague success was enough.

What that makes possible next is straightforward: we can finish the directive semantics without changing the shape again, and we can keep tightening the proof around the paths that matter most. The system is a little less improvisational now. That is the useful kind of progress.





